<HL>
   Steel Production Slips 2%
</HL>
<DATE>
07/19/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN EUROP LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRUSSELS -- Production of crude steel by the 35 countries
that account for 97% of output in the Western world slipped
2% to 39,436,000 tons in June, according to the International
Iron and Steel Institute. The year-earlier figure was
40,258,000 tons.
   Japan, which accounted for 8,982,000 tons, boosted output
0.2%, while the U.S.'s production of 7,357,000 tons was down
0.8%. The European Community output fell 3.9% to 11,662,000
tons. The biggest slump was in Brazil, where production
tumbled 22.4% to 1,519,000 tons.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the first six months, the IISI said output slipped
2.5% to 239,758,000 tons from the July to December 1989
total. Again Brazil was the worst-affected producer. Output
fell 17.6% to 10,124,000 tons.
</TEXT>
